Java-based concurrency model

VS

Akka´s Actor Model

The thread model provides mechanisms as locks: that means deadlocks,  mutable state and difficult at times to debug.


The actor model as a high level concurrency approach that provides levels of concurrency



Actor Model


In 1973 Carl Hewitt, Peter Bishop, Richard Steiger

wrote a paper:

"An universal modular Actor formalism for artificial intelligence"


Actors are independent and do not share their state


Principles


Inmutable messages interchanged between actors in an asynchronously way.


Each actor has a queue.



Sender and receiver actors can be executed in different threads.



Akka framework


Actor Model + high level abstraction of concurrency = Event driven, middleware framework!!


Open source framework available under Apache License, V2


Created by Jonas Bonér and is part of Typesafe Stack

Features

JVM





Location transparency
Transaction support
Event-driven
Fault tolerance
Scalability
Concurrency

Understanding Akka


Actor system: 


A heavyweight structure that will allocate 1..N Threads.

 A collaborative group of actors with assigned sub-tasks.

Several actor systems with different configuration can co-exist into the same JVM

Manages actor behavior, lifecycle, hierarchy, etc






Actor

Actor is an independent, concurrent, computational entity that responds to message.

The smallest unit in the concurrent application that performs a sub-task

There are two kinds: Untyped and typed




Mailbox


Connects the sender and receiver actor, in the mailbox the message is enqueued in the same order as they are sent.


Every actor has exactly one mailbox.


Can be bounded or unbounded.


There is a priority mailbox!!

Dispatcher

It is the heart of the Akka application because it coordinates the message dispatching to the actors

Picks up the messages from the queue and takes them to the actor to be processed.


Dispatcher types


Dispatcher: Default, Event-based, binds a set of actors to a thread pool.


Pinned dispatcher:  Each actor has its own dedicated thread. Ideal for blocking operations.



Balancing dispatcher:  Redistribute the work from busy actors to idle ones.




Calling Thread dispatcher:  Provides a deterministic execution order

It does not create any new threads and can be use for different threads concurrently for the same actor.

The mailboxes are created on demand

A mailbox by Thread

Routers


A router is a type of actor

Routes the incoming messages to the outbound actors.

There are several algorithms to route the messages

There is no router´s mailbox

Futures


A data structure used to encapsulate the result of a concurrent operation.

Can be accessed synchronously or asynchronously

Need an execution context

It is a way to get a reply from an Untyped Actor
